<font color="#996600">Earth</font>, <font color="#FFFF00">Air</font>, <font color="#FF0000">Fire</font>, <font color="#0000FF">Water</font>.....If I had a heart I could summon Captain Planet &gt:)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1525<br> <font color=#333333>(6/19/02 11:12:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1355.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Mage Dots and Cuddas Beneath the Lake of Ill Manners</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Have you ever died of overnuking?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Generally not more than once every few levels, but if you had read the referenced thread on Mage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DoTs</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, you would know that there are several situations where the lowered aggro comes in handy.  Let me name just one.<br>
<br>
Beneath the placid surface of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Lake of Ill Manners</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> lay six static spawns of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Deepwater</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bloodgill Baracuddas</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Each spawn is on a two minute timer, and are never camped <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (unlike the BG Goblins, which always are camped)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
When I was a but a journeyman of 49 seasons, I would immerse myself in the cool waters of the lake, summon, of all things, a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Greater Conjuration: Fire</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and go fishing.  All the cudda's were blue to me, and with six spawns on a two minute timer, there was never any waiting, and I killed 'cuddas almost as fast as they could spawn, a solid blue kill every 150-200 seconds.<br>
<br>
Now these fishies hit hard and fast, and without some help from his faithful master, brave <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would be pierced to smithereens before the foe was dispatched.  And in those days my connection was dial up, so the tactic of chaincasting was denied me.<br>
<br>
The fight was a simple fight.  Pull, perhaps with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Malisement</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and send the pet in.  Let the cudda beat on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s damage shield, and let <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> beat on the cudda in return, with me tipping the scales of the fight by dealing damage from a safe distance.<br>
<br>
But in order to win, I must at all costs avoid getting aggro.  Back in those days, my AC and HP were not what they are today, and as I said, the cuddas strike quick and deadly blows.<br>
<br>
I found that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Swords</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which costs 250 mana and deals 600 mana would always cause unwanted fishly attention, even after it was half dead.  On the other hand, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Elemental Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> also does 600 damage, but costs only 240 mana <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (less, because in those days I was specialization evocation)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It also never took aggro from the pet.  As best as I recall, I would pull with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and send in the pet, who would immediately get and keep aggro.  A second cast, and still I may sit safely in the calm waters and recover my mana while my champion <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does battle on my behalf.  Sometimes, in a close battle, a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Swords</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to finish the foe quickly.<br>
<br>
If I had insisted in trying to use <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Steel</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to do all the damage, yes, I would have died repeatedly.  If I had not used <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Elemental Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I might have given up on the spawn.  But as it was it carried me from 49 to 51 swiftly, after which I switch to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Vocaration: Earth</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Ice Giants</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> ForEverFrost</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Given what else has been written about <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DoTs</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> here, namely that they do a third more damage per tick against a static foe, and with specialization, my choices were:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Maelstrom</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 683 damage for 216 mana, including specialization, for 3.16 damage per mana, or<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, at 600 damage for 244 mana, including specialization, for 2.46 damage per mana, and guaranteed aggro against a fishy foe whose pernicious and persistant piercing would percolate my pink and precious person, well...<br>
<br>
Pretty easy choice.  What some other <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are saying is that they too find circumstances where the Mage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DoTs</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> make sense.<br>
<br>
That is, when chaining pets is not an option, the fight is only winnable when the mage pumps in constant damage, but must never get aggro, then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> DoTs</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> make sense.<br>
<br>
Always eager to learn,<br>
